My meme

My meme is a play on the Two Buttons Choice meme, depicting a superhero (in this case a university student) having to make the difficult choice between paying rent and buying food. Usually this meme is all about making a lighthearted choice - instead I subvert expectations by posing a true and tough daily choice many of us have to make.

library(magick)

#importing in two halves to meme
template1 <- image_read(path = "top half.png")
template2 <- image_read(path = "bottom half.png")

#creating complete meme template
temp.complete <- image_append(c(template1, template2), stack = TRUE)
  

# creating meme:

## first I append the white box below to add a caption, then add the 'rent' and 'food' overlays
meme <- image_append(c(temp.complete, 
               image_blank(width = 391, height = 50, color = "#FFFFFF")), 
             stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "The Classic Student Dilemma",
               color = "#000000",
               size = 30,
               font = "Impact",
               gravity = "south",
               location = "0+10") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Rent             Food",
               color = "#000000",
               size = 30,
               degrees = -10, 
               font = "Impact",
               gravity = "North",
               location = "-40+50")

# saving the meme
image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")

My animated GIF

My animated gif is creative in just how strange it is: where the viewer might expect the word bruh as the final frame (given the other frames are all variants on the word), instead they are greeted with the bruh Kanye image. For the middle two frames the colours are also very tough to look at, so the final image is almost seen as being easier on the eyes!

library(magick)


# creating a vector for the counts
bruh <- image_read("bruh.jpg")

# creating each frame, where the text comes from the counts vector
frame1 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "broh", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame2 <- image_blank(color = "red", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "brah", size = 100, gravity = "north")

frame3 <- image_blank(color = "blue", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "breh", size = 100, gravity = "south")

frame4 <- bruh

# putting the frames in order using a vector
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)

# creating an animation
animation <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

# saving animated gif

image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
